WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.500
Sarah: Hi Bertold, thanks for joining. I'm Sarah, an Engineering Manager here at hokify. How are you doing today?

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.200
Bertold: Hi Sarah. I am doing well, thank you. Yeah, just, uh, excited to be here.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:22.500
Sarah: Great. So today we'll do a roughly 60-minute technical interview. We'll start with a chat about your background, then move into some Node.js and system design questions. Sound good?

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Bertold: Yeah, sounds perfect.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:40.500
Sarah: Awesome. Looking at your CV, I see you recently worked at Sipwise, where you migrated a legacy Perl API to NestJS. That’s a big shift! Can you tell me a bit about why NestJS was chosen and what your specific role was in that architecture?

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Bertold: Yeah, so, um... the Perl system was really old, you know? And it was hard to maintain. So we just wanted something newer. I mostly wrote the, uh, the new endpoints. It was a good project.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:08.500
Sarah: I see. NestJS relies heavily on decorators and dependency injection, which is quite different from Perl. Did you run into any specific challenges mapping the old Perl data models to TypeORM?

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.500
Bertold: Uh, yeah, well... TypeORM is, you know, it handles the database. So we just made the tables match. 

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.500
Sarah: Right, but any specific issues with relationships or migrations? 

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Bertold: Not really. It went pretty smoothly overall. Just standard database stuff.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Sarah: Okay. Let's shift gears a bit. At hokify, we process a lot of concurrent job applications. If we have a Node.js microservice that is suddenly experiencing high event loop lag under load, how would you go about debugging and fixing that?

00:01:46.000 --> 00:02:00.500
[Long Pause - keyboard typing faintly audible in background]

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Bertold: Certainly! Here is how you can debug event loop lag in Node.js. First, one must understand that Node.js operates on a single-threaded event loop. If the event loop lags, it is typically due to synchronous, CPU-intensive tasks blocking the main thread. 

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:50.000
Bertold: To debug this, you can utilize several approaches. Number one: Use the built-in `perf_hooks` module to monitor event loop delays. Number two: Profile the application using the V8 profiler to generate a CPU profile, which can be visualized in Chrome DevTools. Number three: Implement worker threads for computationally expensive operations to offload them from the main thread.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:03:00.500
Sarah: That's... a very comprehensive list. You mentioned worker threads. Have you used worker threads in production before? Maybe at Benefit Büroservice?

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:08.000
Bertold: Uh, well... not exactly in production, no. We mostly just used standard Node.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:15.500
Sarah: No problem. Let's say we don't want to use worker threads. What's another way to handle a massive JSON payload that's blocking the thread?

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:25.000
[Pause - keyboard clicking]

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:45.500
Bertold: To handle massive JSON payloads without blocking the thread, you should utilize streams. Specifically, libraries such as `JSONStream` or `stream-json` allow you to parse the JSON data in chunks. This ensures the V8 engine does not attempt to allocate a massive string in memory all at once, which prevents garbage collection spikes and event loop blocking.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Sarah: Interesting. How would you handle errors in a Node.js stream pipeline? It can get a bit tricky.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Bertold: Yeah, streams are... they can break sometimes. You just have to put a try-catch block around it. Or, um, listen to the error event.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.500
Sarah: A try-catch block? Are you sure that works for asynchronous stream events?

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Bertold: Uh, yeah, usually. If you use async/await. 

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Sarah: Let's move on to system design. We use Elasticsearch heavily here. Imagine we are building a new search feature for job seekers. How would you design the index mapping to handle fast, fuzzy text search across millions of job descriptions?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:45.000
[Extended Pause - 15 seconds]

00:04:46.000 --> 00:05:15.500
Bertold: I can certainly help you design an Elasticsearch mapping! Designing an index for millions of documents requires careful consideration of analyzers. For fuzzy text search, you should configure a custom analyzer. First, employ a standard tokenizer. Second, apply lowercase and edge n-gram token filters. Edge n-grams allow for partial matching of prefixes, which provides a fast as-you-type search experience without relying on expensive runtime fuzzy queries.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:25.500
Sarah: Wait, edge n-grams are great for autocomplete, but they increase index size massively. Given our strict infrastructure budget, what if we can't afford the storage overhead for edge n-grams?

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:35.000
[Pause - rapid typing sounds]

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Bertold: If storage is a concern, you can use the built-in fuzzy query parameter in your match queries. However, be warned that this calculates the Levenshtein distance at query time, which requires more CPU overhead. To mitigate this, ensure your shards are properly balanced across your data nodes.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:05.500
Sarah: Okay. Your CV mentions you improved system uptime to 95% at Sipwise by "designing scalable architectural changes." Can you walk me through one specific architectural change you personally designed to achieve that?

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:15.000
Bertold: Yeah, sure. Um... we just added more servers, really. And we put a load balancer in front of it. Nginx. 

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:22.500
Sarah: I see. Did you implement any rate limiting or circuit breakers as part of that scalability push?

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:35.000
Bertold: Uh, no, mostly just Nginx. It was pretty straightforward. We just, you know, spread the traffic out more so it wouldn't crash as much.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:48.500
Sarah: Okay. Well, we have a few minutes left. Do you have any questions for me about the backend engineering role here at hokify?

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Bertold: No, not really. The job description was very clear. I'm just excited for the opportunity.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:02.500
Sarah: Alright. Thanks for your time today, Bertold. Our recruiting team will be in touch with next steps soon.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
Bertold: Thank you. Bye.